<div id="review_16877152" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/16877152" />
    <a title="GeekChick" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/577893-geekchick"><img alt="GeekChick" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1193411602p2/577893.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/16877152?book_show_action=true">Mar 02, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="GeekChick" class="user" itemprop="url" name="GeekChick" href="/user/show/577893-geekchick">GeekChick</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780553383683" href="/book/show/1305.Gates_of_Fire">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/577893-geekchick?shelf=fictionalized-history">fictionalized-history</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer16877152" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14695790311975647615">When I first tried reading this book about the Battle of Thermopylae, after a while I just had to put it down. I didn&apos;t know if it was because I just didn&apos;t like it, or if it was because it wasn&apos;t the right time to read it. So I tried again.<br/><br/>Forgive me for saying something like this, but it&apos;s clear the book is written by a man. There is way too much detail, but absolutely no emotional foundation. I think one of the reviewers captured it best when he/she commented on Pressfield&apos;s ability in writin</span>
  <span id="freeText14695790311975647615" style="display:none">When I first tried reading this book about the Battle of Thermopylae, after a while I just had to put it down. I didn't know if it was because I just didn't like it, or if it was because it wasn't the right time to read it. So I tried again.<br /><br />Forgive me for saying something like this, but it's clear the book is written by a man. There is way too much detail, but absolutely no emotional foundation. I think one of the reviewers captured it best when he/she commented on Pressfield's ability in writing a "military novel." Need I say more? <br /><br />I am betting my husband would love this. But for me, just when it gets good, Pressfield derails into too much boring, needless detail. I stuck it out pretty far, but after about 2/3, I've decided that there are too many other books in the world to spend any more time on this one. <br /><br />I'm definitely going to see what my hubby thinks, though. When I find out, I'll update my review!</span>
  <a data-text-id="14695790311975647615" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


